"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:9.5\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">9.5</span> Blocks of pressed dried fruit</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אָשִׁישׁ, אֲשִׁישָׁה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’ashish, ’ashishah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam6:19\">2SA 6:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr16:3\">1CH 16:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Song2:5\">SNG 2:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa16:7\">ISA 16:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos3:1\">HOS 3:1</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">דְּבֵלָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(dvelah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam25:18\">1SA 25:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam30:12\">1SA 30:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs20:7\">2KI 20:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Chr12:41\">1CH 12:41</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa38:21\">ISA 38:21</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">παλάθη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(palathē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt10:5\">JDT 10:5</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The fruit of the fig tree was dried in the sun and then pressed together in blocks for storage and for transporting. The same was done with raisins, that is, dried grapes. For blocks of dried fruit used medicinally, see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.15.2 Poultice, fig cake&lt;REALIA:1.15.2&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>For the fig tree and grapevine, see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">Fig&lt;FLORA:2.6&gt;</a> and <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">Vine&lt;FLORA:2.12&gt;</a> respectively. In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam25:18\">1SA 25:18</a><abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"God&#x27;s Word Translation\">GW</abbr> has “fig cakes,” but this rendering is likely to give the misimpression that these were baked cakes with figs in them. Most translations consulted also use the word “cakes” but in a phrase like “cakes of pressed figs” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>), which is slightly better. However, even here the modern reader is most likely to understand “cake” as a baked food. <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr> avoids this problem with “portions of dried figs,” while <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has “handfuls of dried figs.” It will often be possible (and preferable) to say “lumps of pressed figs” or “blocks of dried figs.” Some languages will have a specific word for such blocks of pressed dried fruit.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam30:12\">1SA 30:12</a><abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> has “a piece of a cake of figs,” but <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> is better with “some dried figs.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
